discussion.content:
[Student 3 — Round 4]

I’ll add the **implementation and financing roadmap** we can insert near the end of the report, so our recommendations are operational rather than just analytical.

## 1. Implementation sequence: what governments should do first

We should recommend a clear 2026–2035 sequence:

| Period | Action | Output |
|---|---|---|
| **2026–2027** | Establish AZ–KZ Trans-Caspian Corridor Company | Joint operating platform for tariffs, schedules, booking, data, shipper contracts |
| **2026–2028** | MDB-funded project preparation facility | Independent traffic model, willingness-to-pay study, legal review, SEA/EIA screening |
| **2027–2030** | Maritime Bridge Phase 1 | Ferry charter/procurement, port debottlenecking, digital customs, guaranteed schedules |
| **2030–2035** | Maritime Bridge Phase 2 | Capacity expansion to 20–30 Mt/year, logistics zones, rail-terminal integration |
| **Post-2035** | Fixed-link decision gate | Only proceed if traffic, tariff, capex, legal, and environmental triggers are met |

This makes the fixed link a **conditional option**, not a hidden commitment.

## 2. Financing plan for the preferred program

For the **$3–7B Trans-Caspian Maritime Bridge Program**, a plausible financing stack could be:

| Source | Role |
|---|---|
| Azerbaijan/Kazakhstan budgets | Core public co-financing, customs/port infrastructure |
| EBRD / World Bank / ADB / AIIB | Long-term loans for ports, rail, digital systems, resilience |
| EU Global Gateway | Grants/TA for digital corridor, non-Russian connectivity, customs harmonization |
| Export credit agencies | Ferry/Ro-Ro vessel financing |
| Private operators | Terminal concessions, warehouses, logistics parks |
| China/BRI-linked finance | Selective support for rail/logistics capacity if governance is transparent |
| Climate/resilience funds | Sea-level adaptation, shore power, green vessels where eligible |

This is much easier to syndicate than a $35–90B fixed-link debt package.

## 3. Governance safeguards to recommend

MDBs and private investors will want governance conditions. We should include:

- independent traffic and cost forecasts;
- competitive procurement;
- open-access rules for shippers/operators;
- transparent tariff methodology;
- anti-corruption and audit requirements;
- performance KPIs published quarterly;
- ring-fenced maintenance funding;
- dispute-resolution under neutral arbitration;
- environmental and social monitoring.

These safeguards are especially important because corridor monopolies can become rent-seeking institutions if not regulated.

## 4. Tariff policy: avoid killing demand

The Corridor Company should not simply maximize tolls. It should use a **corridor-competitiveness tariff policy**:

- publish a single through tariff for Alat–Kuryk/Aktau movement;
- offer volume discounts for anchor users;
- differentiate tariffs by cargo type and service level;
- keep bulk cargo charges low enough to maintain volumes;
- charge premium rates only for guaranteed high-speed/reliable container services;
- coordinate with railways so total end-to-end price remains competitive.

This contrasts with the fixed-link JV, where debt pressure would force high tolls and suppress traffic.

## 5. Stakeholder compact before fixed-link SPV

Before any bridge/tunnel SPV, AZ/KZ should negotiate a wider **Middle Corridor Stakeholder Compact** with:

- Georgia and Türkiye for onward rail/BTK capacity;
- China and major logistics companies for volume commitments;
- EU/MDBs for standards and financing support;
- Russia/Iran/Turkmenistan for Caspian consultation;
- ferry operators and ports for transition planning;
- local communities/environmental groups for social license.

This reduces the risk that Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan build capacity the rest of the corridor cannot absorb.

## 6. Final financing conclusion to use

Suggested report wording:

> The bilateral JV concept is viable as a corridor coordination and operating company, but not as the primary financing vehicle for a fixed link. The near-term bankable structure is a modular corridor modernization program financed through MDB loans, sovereign co-financing, grants, vessel leasing, and private terminal/logistics PPPs. A separate fixed-link SPV should be created only after hard demand, environmental, legal, and fiscal tests are satisfied.

This gives policymakers a constructive path: **build the market and institutions first; decide on the mega-link later.**

[Student 3 — Round 5]

I’ll add a **final bankability and institutional-design layer** so the report can answer not only “what should be built?” but “what entity can credibly raise money and manage risk?”

## 1. The proposed bilateral JV needs a narrower mandate

I agree with Student 1 and Student 2: we should not reject Azerbaijan–Kazakhstan cooperation. We should reject the **wrong mandate**.

A bilateral JV is appropriate if its mandate is:

- corridor coordination;
- port/ferry interface management;
- unified tariff publication;
- digital booking/tracking;
- shipper contracts;
- performance KPIs;
- MDB-funded project preparation.

It is **not appropriate yet** if its mandate is:

- raising $35–90B;
- taking full construction risk;
- taking full traffic risk;
- setting high fixed-link tolls to repay debt;
- procuring a bridge/tunnel before demand is proven.

Suggested wording:

> The bilateral JV should first be a corridor-market-building institution, not a mega-construction vehicle.

## 2. Bankability checklist for any future fixed-link SPV

If policymakers insist on preserving the fixed-link concept, the final report should include a lender-style checklist. A future SPV should not reach financial close unless it has:

| Requirement | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Independent P90 capex estimate | Prevents politically optimistic cost assumptions |
| Binding take-or-pay or capacity contracts | Converts traffic forecasts into bankable revenue |
| Sovereign support agreement | Covers demand shortfall, force majeure, and availability payments |
| MDB environmental clearance | Necessary for EBRD/World Bank/AIIB participation |
| Debt-sustainability assessment | Especially important for Azerbaijan |
| Regional legal consultation record | Reduces Caspian Convention/navigation objections |
| Corridor-wide capacity plan | Ensures Georgia/Türkiye/BTK links can absorb traffic |
| Transparent tariff methodology | Prevents monopoly pricing and shipper distrust |
| Lifecycle maintenance reserve | Avoids underfunding after construction |
| Political-risk insurance / MIGA-type cover | Needed for international lenders |

Without these, the project would not be financeable even if engineering feasibility were proven.

## 3. Financing sources should be matched to risk appetite

We should be explicit that different financiers will fund different parts of the program:

| Investor/lender type | Likely appetite |
|---|---|
| MDBs | Ports, rail, customs, resilience, feasibility, environmental studies |
| Export credit agencies | Ferries, port equipment, signaling, rail systems |
| Private infrastructure funds | Terminals/logistics parks with predictable concession revenue |
| Commercial banks | Shorter-tenor loans if MDBs/sovereigns de-risk |
| China/BRI lenders | Selective rail/logistics/fixed-link interest, but likely tied to contractors |
| EU Global Gateway | Soft infrastructure, non-Russian connectivity, digitalization |
| Sovereign wealth/Gulf investors | Logistics zones and real estate-linked development |
| Private equity | Ancillary logistics services, not fixed-link traffic risk |

This helps us avoid implying there is one giant financing pool for the whole project.

## 4. Tariff governance is critical

A fixed-link JV under debt pressure might set tolls too high and undermine the corridor. The corridor company should instead use **regulated corridor pricing**:

- one transparent through-tariff for the Caspian leg;
- differentiated rates by cargo type and service level;
- volume discounts for anchor shippers;
- premium services for time-sensitive containers;
- lower rates for bulk cargo to preserve volume;
- periodic review by an independent regulator or bilateral tariff board.

This is important because the goal is not maximum toll per ton; it is **maximum sustainable corridor competitiveness**.

## 5. Procurement model recommendation

For the near-term Maritime Bridge Program, procurement can be modular:

- vessel leasing/procurement through competitive tenders;
- port terminals through PPP concessions;
- digital platform through performance-based technology contracts;
- rail/berth works through MDB-compliant EPC contracts;
- logistics zones through land-lease concessions.

For any future fixed link, we should recommend **not** using a single politically negotiated EPC contract. It would need:

- independent owner’s engineer;
- open international tendering;
- staged design-build packages;
- cost-overrun sharing;
- transparent change-order rules;
- anti-corruption monitoring;
- public disclosure aligned with MDB standards.

## 6. One refinement to the “China/BRI” point

China’s strategic interest does not automatically equal willingness to subsidize the project. Beijing may support the Middle Corridor as redundancy, but Chinese shippers will still compare cost, reliability, and political risk. So final wording should be:

> China may be a strategic partner and potential financier, but Chinese participation should be treated as conditional on route competitiveness and governance, not assumed as a blank cheque for the fixed link.

## 7. Final financing conclusion to carry into the report

Proposed paragraph:

> The most effective financing structure is a staged institutional model: create a Trans-Caspian Corridor Company now to coordinate and commercialize existing and upgraded services; establish an MDB-supervised project preparation facility for fixed-link studies; and defer any fixed-link SPV until hard bankability tests are met. A tariff-funded bilateral mega-JV would expose both governments—especially Azerbaijan—to excessive fiscal, demand, construction, and environmental risk.

[Student 2 — Round 6]

I’ll add a final **logistics/legal wording calibration** so our report is precise and not vulnerable to pushback from transport ministries or MDB reviewers.

## 1. Be careful with the “15 days faster than sea” claim

The prompt says the Middle Corridor reduces travel time by 15 days versus traditional sea routes. We can use that, but should phrase it as **route- and cargo-specific**:

> The Middle Corridor can be materially faster than Suez maritime shipping for selected China–Europe cargoes, but its advantage depends on reliable rail schedules, Caspian crossing performance, customs processing, and onward capacity through Georgia/Türkiye/Europe.

This prevents overclaiming. The fixed link improves one leg, but the corridor’s time advantage disappears if cargo waits at borders, ports, gauge-change points, or terminals.

## 2. Fixed link does not eliminate all interoperability constraints

Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan both use broad-gauge rail systems, which helps across the Caspian. But the wider corridor still faces:

- gauge/interface issues toward Türkiye/Europe;
- BTK and Georgia/Türkiye capacity limits;
- wagon/container availability;
- hazardous cargo rules;
- customs and security inspections;
- liability handoffs between railways/operators.

So final report should say:

> A fixed link would reduce the maritime transshipment bottleneck but would not create a seamless China–Europe land bridge unless rail, customs, digital documentation, and onward European interfaces are upgraded simultaneously.

## 3. Route wording: Alat–Kuryk should be the default study case

I agree with earlier comments that we should not overstate route certainty, but for analysis:

- **Alat–Kuryk** is likely the more logical fixed-link study alignment because Kuryk is more ferry/Ro-Ro oriented and likely involves fewer urban-port conflicts.
- **Alat–Aktau** remains important for complementary port capacity and logistics but may be less attractive as the principal fixed-link endpoint.

Suggested wording:

> Any future fixed-link pre-feasibility should compare Alat–Kuryk and Alat–Aktau, but Alat–Kuryk should be treated as the initial reference alignment for freight-focused corridor analysis.

## 4. Legal section: avoid implying the Caspian Convention directly authorizes a bridge

We should phrase the 2018 Convention carefully:

> The Convention clarifies aspects of Caspian legal status and sovereign rights, but it does not provide a turnkey approval regime for a 300–370 km fixed link. Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan would still need a project-specific treaty, seabed-use arrangements, navigation protections, environmental approvals, customs/security rules, and consultation with other littoral states where ecological, navigation, or security interests may be affected.

Also mention Tehran Convention compliance and transboundary EIA good practice, without getting too deep into treaty law.

## 5. Environmental baseline must precede route commitment

Before even a full feasibility study, the project needs baseline screening on:

- seal and sturgeon sensitivity zones;
- coastal wetlands and bird migration corridors;
- contaminated sediment risk near hydrocarbon infrastructure;
- shipping lanes and navigation safety;
- hydrological effects of any causeway/artificial-island component;
- sea-level decline impacts on approaches and port interfaces.

This supports our stage-gate logic: **route selection should follow environmental screening, not precede it.**

## 6. Add one more “do not overbuild before demand” logistics point

The Maritime Bridge Program should be designed to test real demand:

- scheduled sailings;
- guaranteed port dwell-time targets;
- unified tariff;
- shipper contracts;
- digital documentation;
- reliable service reporting.

If shippers still do not commit after those improvements, that is strong evidence against a fixed link. If demand grows beyond the upgraded system’s capacity, that becomes evidence for feasibility.

## 7. Suggested final sentence for logistics/legal conclusion

> The fixed link’s main value would be reliability, not simply distance reduction. But reliability is corridor-wide: unless Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan solve customs, port, rail, legal, environmental, and onward-capacity issues first, a bridge or tunnel would risk becoming an exceptionally expensive link between remaining bottlenecks.

[Student 3 — Round 6]

I’ll add a final **institutional and contractual design** layer. We have agreed that the bilateral JV should exist, but its legal mandate and balance sheet need to be designed carefully so it does not become a disguised bridge-construction vehicle.

## 1. Corridor Company should be asset-light at first

The Trans-Caspian Corridor Company should not initially own all ports, ferries, terminals, and rail assets. That would create valuation disputes and political complexity. Better first mandate:

- coordinate schedules;
- publish unified tariffs;
- manage digital booking/tracking;
- negotiate shipper capacity agreements;
- monitor KPIs;
- standardize documentation and liability rules;
- coordinate MDB-backed upgrades.

Physical assets can remain with existing port authorities, railways, ferry operators, and terminal companies, with service-level agreements signed to the Corridor Company.

Suggested wording:

> The Corridor Company should begin as an operating and coordination platform, not as a capital-intensive asset owner.

## 2. Separate asset-level SPVs for bankable components

For the Maritime Bridge Program, financing should be divided into smaller SPVs or project packages:

| Package | Best structure |
|---|---|
| Ferry/Ro-Ro fleet | Leasing company or vessel SPV with ECA/MDB support |
| Port berths/equipment | Port authority borrowing or terminal PPP |
| Digital platform | Service contract or concession |
| Logistics zones | Land-lease PPPs/private developers |
| Rail-terminal upgrades | National railway/MDB sovereign-backed loans |
| Sea-level adaptation | Sovereign/MDB/climate-resilience finance |

This avoids putting the entire $3–7B program on one JV balance sheet and makes each component more financeable.

## 3. Revenue model for the Corridor Company

The Corridor Company can fund itself through modest, transparent fees rather than heavy tolls:

- booking/platform fee per shipment;
- coordination fee embedded in through-tariff;
- premium service fee for guaranteed slots;
- data/API access for logistics firms;
- management fee from participating ports/railways;
- performance bonuses if dwell-time and reliability targets are met.

This is important because the company’s purpose is to **reduce friction**, not extract monopoly rent.

## 4. Governance design to prevent political deadlock

A 50/50 Azerbaijan–Kazakhstan entity risks deadlock. We should recommend:

- equal strategic oversight but professional management;
- independent CEO/CFO selected competitively;
- independent board members acceptable to MDBs;
- reserved matters requiring both governments;
- operational matters delegated to management;
- neutral arbitration mechanism;
- transparent tariff methodology;
- audited annual accounts;
- KPI disclosure.

If Georgia/Türkiye/China/EU actors are not shareholders, they can still sit on an advisory council.

## 5. Future fixed-link SPV should be conditional and ring-fenced

If the project later passes triggers, the Fixed Link SPV should be legally separate from the Corridor Company. This protects the functioning maritime corridor from being financially contaminated by bridge/tunnel debt.

Future SPV requirements:

- ring-fenced debt;
- no cross-default to port/ferry assets;
- sovereign support agreement explicitly approved by both governments;
- MDB environmental and procurement standards;
- maintenance reserve account;
- independent tariff regulator or tariff board;
- step-in rights for lenders;
- political-risk cover where available.

## 6. Don’t let “availability payments” hide fiscal risk

If a future fixed link is financed through availability payments, it may appear bankable to lenders because governments guarantee revenue. But from a public-finance perspective, that is still debt-like exposure.

Final report should warn:

> Availability payments can make the project financeable, but they do not make it free; they transfer demand risk from lenders to taxpayers.

So any availability-payment model needs parliamentary/budget disclosure and debt-sustainability review.

## 7. Final institutional recommendation

Proposed paragraph for the report:

> Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan should establish a bilateral Trans-Caspian Corridor Company in 2026 with an asset-light mandate focused on coordination, digitalization, tariffs, service standards, and shipper contracts. Physical investments should be financed through separate asset-level SPVs, port authorities, railway companies, vessel leases, and PPP concessions. A fixed-link SPV should not be created until the project passes hard demand, environmental, legal, fiscal, and bankability tests. This staged institutional model preserves strategic ambition while avoiding premature fiscal exposure.

[Student 5 — Round 6]

I’ll add a final **quality-control layer on the preferred Maritime Bridge Program**, because our report should not make it sound risk-free. We need to show that we have stress-tested our own recommendation.

## 1. The Maritime Bridge Program also has execution risks

Even though it is clearly preferable to immediate fixed-link construction, it can still fail if poorly coordinated.

| Risk | Why it matters | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|
| Fragmented governance | Ports, ferries, railways, customs may optimize separately | Corridor Company with binding service-level agreements |
| Underused new vessels | Demand may not grow as forecast | Phase procurement; use charter/leasing before full fleet purchase |
| Port upgrades without rail capacity | Cargo may shift bottleneck inland | Tie port investment to rail paths, wagon pools, BTK/onward capacity |
| Digital platform not adopted | Shippers still face paper/customs delays | Make digital documents mandatory for corridor incentives |
| Tariff fragmentation | Total route cost remains unpredictable | Publish unified through-tariff and service guarantees |
| Sea-level adaptation underestimated | Ports may remain vulnerable | Include climate-resilience engineering in all port works |
| Political coordination fatigue | Initial cooperation may fade | MDB-linked KPIs and disbursement conditions |

This makes our preferred option more credible: it is lower-risk, not no-risk.

## 2. Add “service reliability” as the central KPI

The final report should not only measure tons/year. Shippers care about predictability.

Key reliability KPIs:

- percentage of shipments delivered within scheduled window;
- average and maximum port dwell time;
- ferry cancellation/weather-delay rate;
- customs clearance time;
- end-to-end Alat–Kuryk/Aktau crossing time;
- number of documents required per shipment;
- percentage of shipments under through-bill-of-lading;
- claim/dispute resolution time.

This will help the Corridor Company prove value before any fixed-link decision.

## 3. Social and safety issues deserve a short section

For both the fixed link and the maritime upgrade, we should mention:

- worker safety during construction and port operations;
- emergency response capacity for hazardous cargo;
- search-and-rescue coordination on the Caspian;
- local employment and skills training;
- community consultation near Alat, Kuryk, and Aktau;
- transition planning for existing ferry operators/workers if services are reorganized.

For a future fixed link, emergency response is especially serious: a rail or road incident 150 km offshore would require a dedicated safety architecture, adding cost and complexity.

## 4. Do not let the report imply ferries are obsolete

Even in a future fixed-link scenario, ferry capacity should remain part of the system because it provides:

- redundancy during bridge/tunnel maintenance or closure;
- flexibility for oversized/hazardous cargo;
- competitive pressure on fixed-link tariffs;
- backup during accidents, security incidents, or technical failures.

Suggested wording:

> The long-term objective should be a resilient multimodal Caspian crossing system, not dependence on a single asset.

## 5. Final report should include a “decision not construction” recommendation

I suggest we phrase the immediate next step as:

> The consortium should finance decisions, institutions, and market tests before financing concrete and steel.

That means funding:

- independent demand/willingness-to-pay study;
- strategic environmental and social assessment;
- corridor digital platform;
- unified tariff and legal framework;
- phased port/ferry/rail upgrades;
- shipper capacity-contract negotiations.

This aligns with MDB discipline and avoids premature political commitment.

## 6. Add a final audience-specific message

| Audience | Message |
|---|---|
| Azerbaijan/Kazakhstan governments | Build transit power now, but avoid fiscal overreach |
| MDBs | Support modular, transparent, climate-resilient corridor upgrades |
| Private investors | Invest in terminals, logistics parks, vessels, digital systems — not full fixed-link traffic risk |
| China/EU shippers | Corridor reliability and compliance will improve before any mega-link |
| Local communities | Development benefits require jobs, safeguards, and environmental monitoring |

## 7. Final polish sentence

I suggest we close the report with:

> The strategic prize is not the bridge itself; it is a reliable, financeable, sanctions-resilient Middle Corridor. The fixed link may one day serve that objective, but the investable path today is to build demand, reliability, institutions, and regional trust through phased maritime-port-rail modernization.

[Student 3 — Round 8]

I’ll add a **report-ready financing and stakeholder-management section outline** so our final answer has a concrete implementation path, not just a recommendation to defer the fixed link.

## 1. Financing conclusion: three separate vehicles, not one mega-JV

We should recommend a staged institutional architecture:

| Vehicle | Timing | Purpose | Financing role |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Trans-Caspian Corridor Company** | 2026 onward | Coordinate tariffs, schedules, booking, KPIs, shipper contracts | Asset-light; funded by platform/coordination fees and public support |
| **Project Preparation Facility** | 2026–2030 | Fixed-link pre-feasibility, E&S screening, legal work, traffic studies | MDB/EU/AIIB/World Bank/EBRD technical assistance and grants |
| **Fixed-Link SPV** | Only after hard triggers | Finance/build/operate bridge/tunnel if justified | Sovereign-backed, MDB-disciplined, with take-or-pay/availability support |

Key message:

> Do not put fixed-link debt on the balance sheet of the Corridor Company. The corridor must remain financially healthy even if the fixed link never proceeds.

## 2. Project Preparation Facility: useful but should not imply commitment

We should define this carefully. It would fund:

- independent demand and willingness-to-pay study;
- “fixed-link-payable traffic” assessment;
- Alat–Kuryk vs Alat–Aktau route screening;
- P90 cost estimate and construction-risk review;
- strategic environmental and social assessment;
- Caspian legal/treaty analysis;
- consultation with Russia, Iran, Turkmenistan;
- corridor-wide capacity study including Georgia/Türkiye/BTK.

But we should state:

> Funding project preparation is not approval to build. It is a low-cost option-preservation exercise.

## 3. Financing stack for the preferred Maritime Bridge Program

For the $3–7B phased program, final report should show a plausible capital stack:

| Component | Best financing route |
|---|---|
| Ferries/Ro-Ro/rail ferries | Vessel leasing, ECAs, MDB loans, operator equity |
| Port berths/equipment | Port authority borrowing, EBRD/AIIB/World Bank loans |
| Digital customs/platform | EU grants, MDB technical assistance, service concession |
| Rail terminals/wagon pools | National railways + MDB/sovereign-backed loans |
| Logistics zones | PPP land leases, private logistics/warehouse investors |
| Sea-level adaptation | Sovereign/MDB/climate-resilience finance |

This shows investors there are bankable sub-projects even if the fixed link is not bankable.

## 4. Stakeholder compact should precede any fixed-link SPV

Before bridge/tunnel procurement, Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan should secure a **Middle Corridor Stakeholder Compact** covering:

- Azerbaijan/Kazakhstan: tariff policy, customs, security, investment responsibilities;
- Georgia/Türkiye: onward rail and BTK capacity;
- China/logistics firms: capacity commitments and service requirements;
- EU/MDBs: governance, sanctions compliance, environmental standards;
- Russia/Iran/Turkmenistan: Caspian consultation on navigation/ecology/security;
- ferry/port operators: transition or integration plan;
- local communities: jobs, safety, environmental monitoring.

This reduces the risk of building a Caspian asset that the wider corridor cannot use efficiently.

## 5. Future fixed-link bankability checklist

If the project reaches Gate 3, lenders should require:

- binding take-or-pay/capacity contracts covering a material share of debt service;
- sovereign support agreement or explicit availability-payment mechanism;
- independent P90 capex estimate;
- MDB-compliant environmental clearance;
- debt-sustainability analysis, especially for Azerbaijan;
- lifecycle maintenance reserve;
- transparent tariff formula;
- political-risk insurance/MIGA-type cover where available;
- lender step-in rights;
- no cross-default with the Maritime Bridge Program.

This reinforces that a “PPP” label is not enough; real risk allocation must be credible.

## 6. Final financing paragraph for the report

Suggested wording:

> The bilateral Azerbaijan–Kazakhstan structure is useful as a corridor-market-building platform, but not as a stand-alone mega-project financing vehicle. Near-term investment should be modular and financed through MDB loans, grants, vessel leasing, ECAs, sovereign co-financing, and private terminal/logistics PPPs. A fixed-link SPV should be created only after hard traffic, tariff, legal, environmental, and fiscal triggers are met. Otherwise, the proposed JV would expose both governments—especially Azerbaijan—to excessive demand, construction, and debt risk.

[Student 3 — Round 11]

Good additions from Students 1 and 2. I’ll add a **commercial-contracting layer**, because our recommendation depends on proving demand through commitments, not forecasts.

## 1. Move from MoUs to bankable capacity contracts

The final report should warn that political MoUs with shippers or railways are not enough. For either the Maritime Bridge Program or a future fixed link, the corridor needs a ladder of increasingly firm commitments:

| Stage | Instrument | Bankability value |
|---|---|---:|
| Market sounding | Non-binding shipper feedback | Low |
| Strategic MoU | Political/commercial interest | Low/moderate |
| Framework agreement | Indicative volumes, service needs | Moderate |
| Capacity reservation | User pays for guaranteed slots | High |
| Take-or-pay contract | User pays even if capacity unused | Very high |
| Minimum revenue guarantee | Government/anchor user backs revenue floor | Very high, but fiscal risk |

Suggested wording:

> The decisive test is not whether shippers express interest, but whether they will sign multi-year capacity or take-or-pay contracts at tariffs consistent with capital recovery.

## 2. Use the Maritime Bridge Program as a revenue testbed

The Corridor Company should use upgraded ferry/port services to test commercial products before any fixed-link decision:

- premium container slots with guaranteed sailing windows;
- block-train/ferry packages for Kazakhstan–Azerbaijan–Türkiye flows;
- volume contracts for grain, metals, fertilizer and petrochemicals;
- Ro-Ro/truck reservations with digital pre-clearance;
- delay-compensation clauses to prove reliability standards.

If customers will not pay for reliable scheduled ferry capacity, they are unlikely to support fixed-link tolls.

## 3. Revenue-sharing rules are needed to avoid AZ–KZ disputes

A Corridor Company could fail if Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan fight over revenue allocation. We should recommend a transparent formula:

- platform/booking fees retained by Corridor Company;
- port handling revenues retained by relevant port operators;
- rail revenues retained by national railways under published tariffs;
- corridor premium-service surcharge shared by agreed formula;
- reinvestment reserve for maintenance, digital systems and service improvement;
- independent audit of volumes, dwell times and fee collection.

This matters because a 50/50 political company can still deadlock if cashflows are unclear.

## 4. MDB disbursement should be tied to performance milestones

For the Maritime Bridge Program, MDB loans/grants should not be disbursed only against construction outputs. They should be tied to service outcomes:

- port dwell time reductions;
- percentage of shipments digitally documented;
- number of guaranteed sailings per week;
- schedule reliability;
- signed shipper capacity contracts;
- customs pre-clearance adoption;
- private investment mobilized in logistics zones.

This aligns financing with actual corridor performance, not just assets purchased.

## 5. Final contractual condition for future fixed-link SPV

Before any fixed-link financial close, require:

> binding contracts or public guarantees covering a material share of annual debt service for at least the first 10–15 operating years.

Otherwise lenders will treat long-run traffic forecasts as speculative, especially given geopolitical route-switching risk.

## 6. Suggested final insert

> The corridor should be commercialized before it is concretized. Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan should first prove demand through scheduled services, transparent tariffs, and binding capacity contracts on the maritime corridor. Only if users demonstrate willingness to pay for reliability should governments consider transferring that demand base into a fixed-link SPV.

[Student 5 — Round 11]

I’ll add a final **scenario-planning and decision-governance layer**, because the report should help policymakers manage uncertainty over the next 10–15 years rather than make a one-time yes/no decision.

## 1. Add 2035 scenario planning to the final report

We should include a simple future-scenario table showing how the recommendation changes depending on actual market development.

| 2035 scenario | Indicators | Recommended action |
|---|---|---|
| **Low-demand case** | Corridor remains below ~10–15 Mt/year; shippers avoid long-term commitments | Continue Maritime Bridge improvements selectively; do not advance fixed link |
| **Managed-growth case** | 20–30 Mt/year; upgraded ferries/ports near capacity; reliability improving | Launch full fixed-link feasibility and E&S/legal studies, but no construction commitment |
| **High-growth case** | 50–60 Mt/year equivalent demand; high-yield cargo share; take-or-pay contracts | Consider Fixed-Link SPV if P90 capex/legal/EIA tests are clean |
| **Strategic-crisis case** | Russia/Iran/Suez disruption creates urgent public-security value | Treat fixed link as strategic public project, not commercial JV; require explicit fiscal subsidy analysis |

This helps show our approach is adaptive: the fixed link is not rejected forever, but must be justified by observed conditions.

## 2. Create an independent review mechanism

Given the political symbolism of a fixed link, we should recommend an **Independent Corridor Investment Review Panel** before Gate 2 and Gate 3 decisions.

Membership could include:

- Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan transport/finance ministries;
- MDB representatives;
- independent engineering cost experts;
- environmental/social safeguard experts;
- logistics/shipping industry representatives;
- neutral financial advisers.

Mandate:

- validate traffic forecasts;
- review P90 capex assumptions;
- test tariff affordability;
- audit environmental/legal readiness;
- confirm whether stage-gate conditions are met.

Suggested wording:

